<TITLE> 62 face mutiny charges in Feni court </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Feni, Jan 24 (bdnews24.com)Trial of suspected border guards of Feni region, who had expressed solidarity with the bloody rebellion at BDR headquarter at Peelkhana in Dhaka last February, resumed on Sunday after a month-long recess. A special court for the trial, set up at 19 Rifles Battalion headquarter at Jailashkar under Daganbhuiyan Upazila, convened at around 10am. Some 62 border guards, detained in jail, were produced before the court at around 9am. Charges will be framed against the accused, Lt Col Gazi Salauddin told reporters. The proceedings will continue up to 5pm, he said. BDR director general Major General Moinul Islam is heading the three-member panel of judges. Daganbhuiyan police filed a case accusing the 62 border guards for their alleged links with the bloody rebellion at BDR headquarters in Dhaka on February 25-26. The accused also allegedly fired shots and blocked the Feni-Maizdi Road on February 26. They were produced before the Feni divisional judicial magistrate's court on May 14, and have been detained in Feni jail since then. The BDR mutiny trial at Feni began on December 20. The first trial of the BDR mutiny suspects began in Rangamati on November 24, followed by trials at Satkhira on December 7. The bloody February 25-26 mutiny at the BDR headquarters killed over 73 people, 57 of them army officers deputed to the paramilitary force. The rebellion also spread to other BDR outposts around the country. On November 15, the government formed six special courts, including two in Dhaka, to try some 3,500 border guards accused in some 40 cases around the country. bd
